<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>ELECTRICAL SYSTEM TROUBLESHOOTING GUIDE - 9800 - SINGLE REDUCTION, SINGLE SPEED AXLES: SPICER D135-S,
        F155-S, F170-S SERIES - ASSEMBLE - PINION
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="assemble" graphiccount="14">
        <title>PINION</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk document="s14014_15.xml" xrefid="f1401419">Figure 19</hotlnk>.
        </para>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press inner pinion bearing cone onto the pinion gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401439">Figure 39</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401439" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401439" filename="../figg14/g1401439.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 39. Inner Pinion Bearing Cone Into Gear</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press roller bearing onto the pinion gear (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401440">Figure 40</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401440" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401440" filename="../figg14/g1401440.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 40. Roller Bearing Into Pinion Gear</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Stake roller bearing in six places (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401441">Figure 41</hotlnk>), using a staking tool. Refer to
                <hotlnk document="s14014_31.xml" xrefid="hl1401401">SPECIAL TOOLS</hotlnk>
                .
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401441" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401441" filename="../figg14/g1401441.webp" type="webp" resolution="72"/>
                <caption>Figure 41. Stake Roller Bearings</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Make sure all cage bores are free of nicks, dirt, or any contamination.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install inner pinion bearing cup into pinion cage (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401442">Figure 42</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401442" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401442" filename="../figg14/g1401442.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 42. Install Inner Pinion Bearing Cup</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install outer pinion bearing cup into pinion cage (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401443">Figure 43</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401443" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401443" filename="../figg14/g1401443.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 43. Install Outer Pinion Bearing Cup</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Use a feeler gauge or shim stock .0015 inch (.0381 mm) to ensure bearing cups are completely
                seated in bearing bores (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401444">Figure 44</hotlnk>). This is necessary for proper pinion position.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401444" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401444" filename="../figg14/g1401444.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 44. Seating Bearing Cups</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place selective preload spacer that was removed during disassembly onto pinion (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401445">Figure 45</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401445" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401445" filename="../figg14/g1401445.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 45. Replacing Selective Preload Spacer</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place pinion cage onto pinion gear inner bearing (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401446">Figure 46</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401446" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401446" filename="../figg14/g1401446.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 46. Pinion Cage Onto Inner Bearing</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install outer pinion bearing cone onto pinion (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401447">Figure 47</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401447" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401447" filename="../figg14/g1401447.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 47. Outer Pinion Bearing Cone Onto Pinion</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Inspect end yoke or flange seal surface for grooves caused by lip of seal. If grooves can be
                detected with fingernail, it should be replaced.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Install end yoke without seal so that bearing preload can be checked (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401448">Figure 48</hotlnk>). Refer to the
                <hotlnk document="s14014_31.xml" xrefid="hl1401405">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>, for pinion nut torque.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401448" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401448" filename="../figg14/g1401448.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 48. End Yoke Installation</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Pinion cage should be rotated while tightening pinion nut to seat and align the pinion
                        bearings.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>There are two methods of measuring pinion bearing preload and both are acceptable. Both methods
                measure torque to rotate.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To measure preload with the spring scale, clamp the end yoke horizontally in a soft-jawed
                vise. Attach one end of cord to a bolt hole in the pinion cage, wrap cord around pinion cage and attach
                the other end of cord to the spring scale (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401449">Figure 49</hotlnk>). Rotate pinion cage by pulling scale. Read scale during
                fourth revolution. Scale reading must be between 3 and 8 lbs.
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401449" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401449" filename="../figg14/g1401449.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 49. Measuring Preload With Spring Scale</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">To measure preload with an inch pound torque wrench, assemble pinion cage into the carrier
                housing and install two mounting bolts to anchor the unit. Rotate pinion gear with a torque wrench (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401450">Figure 50</hotlnk>). Torque measurement will be taken during fourth revolution
                and must be between 10 and 30 in-lbs. (1.1 and 3.4 N&#8226;m).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401450" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401450" filename="../figg14/g1401450.webp" type="webp"/>
                <caption>Figure 50. Rotating Pinion Gear With Torque Wrench</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When preload reading does not fall within allowable limits, bearing load can be increased by
                        using a thinner spacer or decreased by using a thicker spacer.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>.001" (.025 mm) change in preload spacer thickness changes scale reading by approximately 10
                        lbs. .001" change in preload spacer will change torque to rotate by approximately 30 in-lbs.
                        (3.4 N&#8226;m). (This is only a guide. Individual carriers may vary slightly.)
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>Refer to ,
                <hotlnk xrefid="hl1401406">Spacer Thickness Table</hotlnk>, for available spacer thicknesses. Measure
                spacer before assembly to assure correct thickness.
